content.text:
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "editor",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Keep headers — practical + matches essays' own style",
    "content": "Keep the headers. Two reasons.\n\nFirst, practical: at 2,300 words with 8 distinct topics, continuous prose would feel like a wall. The headers let a reader scan, orient, and return. A reader who finishes Essay 4 and wants to re-check the 形 reinterpretation explanation should be able to find it in seconds. Without headers, they would have to re-read the entire Preface.\n\nSecond, the headers actually mirror the collection's own formatting. The essays themselves use section headers extensively — Essay 4 has 形而上, 客观世界, 非理性 as headers; Essay 6 has formal section breaks throughout. A headerless Preface would be more formally polished than the essays it introduces, which creates a mismatch. The Preface should feel like it belongs to the same working document.\n\nOne refinement: the current headers are functional but slightly dry (\"The Author,\" \"A Bilingual Collection\"). If the author wants more character, some could be sharpened — for example, \"Fish and Fishing\" is already good, \"The Reinterpretation of 形 as Phenomena\" is good, but \"A Note on Reading\" could become \"How to Read This Collection\" or simply \"Reading Order.\" Minor polish, not urgent. The current headers work as-is."
  }
}
